metadata.name: Balanced #151
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: Organicon, variation II #24
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
One of 128 unique generators creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation II is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. A small counter in the lower-right corner displays the progress.

Interface: on first load the piece operates in active mode. In this mode an iteration is cleared 30s after completion and replaced by the next iteration. This mode is indicated by a flashing dot in the upper-right corner.

A first mouse click disables active mode. The current iteration will complete and remain on screen. A second mouse click clears the screen, loads the next iteration, and reenables active mode.

metadata.name: Negative Space #320

- red

Press any key to download a hi-res png.

p5.js script with a custom shader. Depending on the settings, it take some time to fully render / draw.

metadata.name: Skyscapes #3
metadata.description:
When I was a teenager, I heard a man speaking on the radio late at night about how you should go outside and look at the sky. Lie flat on your back and look at the stars, he said. Look at the air between you and them. Think about that distance. Look at each individual pin light. Try to count them. Take in the whole sky all at once and feel the earth against your shoulders. Then, he said, imagine you are looking down. 

-----------

Fully generated live with code, no pngs/jpegs etc.

Press 's' to download 3500px wide image.
Press 'd' to download 6000px wide image (may be slow).

(May load unreliably on some older devices)

metadata.name: Euphonic #1063
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moiré effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: <iframes> #373
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Square Planets #416
metadata.description:
Square Planets was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Planetary Folklore Participations No. 2. (c. 1970). Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the third in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

Square Planets consists of four layers of squares contained within a background square superimposed on top of one another. Each layer is translated from the previous layer but still lies within its boundaries. The background color of each layer is random and its set of squares are another random color. The squares that make up layers two and three are rotated either clockwise or counter-clockwise some random number of degrees within a predetermined range. 

There are many Gestalt interactions within this piece. Layers (square planets) interact with each other in interesting ways. Each new generation with its random color assignments significantly affect your depth perception. Layers appear to come forward or recede. Sometimes there is more "after-imagism" between the square sets. Candy for your mind.

metadata.name: Ripples #40
metadata.description:
Ripples - Made by Zoltan Szalay @insgraphizm with P5.js
April 2022, Hungary

Features
--------
7 color themes
Light or Dark background
Number of rings
Detail of noise

Keyboard control
----------------
[f] toggle fullscreen and hide cursor
[space] manually generate new composition
[a] automatically generate new composition
[s] save image

Touchscreen
-----------
Tap left edge to automatically or right edge to manually generate a new composition.

metadata.name: Vlinder #22
metadata.description:
An homage to the incredible diversity of nature. I did a precursor to these butterflies (vlinder, in Dutch) all the way back in 2016. Google 'butterfly effect shadertoy' to see it.

The entire thing is procedurally generated in a shader that has about 500 lines of code. 

There is A LOT of variety in them: wing shape, pattern, body shape, antennae, colors, as well as some very rare traits that will only come out with a large enough number of editions. A bunch of them can look kind of bland, but every once in a while you get a real beauty! To save an image, just right-click -> 'save as image'

I hope that down the line it will be possible to 'mate' two vlinders and then generate new 'offspring' vlinders that are a mix of their parents. Someone made a shadertoy that does exactly that with my original 2016 effect and its super cool. So, fxhash, if you are reading this... ;)
